Guitar string tension¶

This notebook is about string tension on a standard classical 6-string guitar. The theory however can be applied to any stretched string like those in a piano, on a tennis racket and on bowed instruments like the violin.

In [9]:
Image(filename='data/strings.png', width='200')
Out[9]:

Why string calculation is useful¶

With a bit of algebra you might get a better understanding of the effects of tension, material, diameter and length on the string frequencies on your instrument.

  • you may want to check the manufacturer provided tensions by measuring length, diameter and mass by yourself
  • caculate the string tension when tuning strings differently, for example:
    • quite often the 6th string (E low) is tuned down from E to D giving it a 73.416 Hz pitch
    • playing early Spanish music from Hispanae Citharae Ars Viva requires tuning down the 3rd string by half a semi-tone from G to F# (pitch 184.997 Hz)
  • comparing string brands when restringing: medium tension of brand A might be low tension of brand B. Awareness of the tension can help in your string choice.
  • you may want to know the effect of other string material on the tension. There are differences between nylon, gut and carbon strings.

Mersenne's Laws¶

The theory that a string's frequency (or pitch) depends on length, tension and mass per unit length was decribed by the Frenchman Marin Mersenne in Harmonie Universelle in 1636. Mersenne's equations on natural or fundamental frequency:

  • $f_0 \propto \frac{1}{L}$
    The frequency is inversely proportional to the length of the string. A longer string has a lower frequency. This actually originates from Pythagoras.
  • $f_0 \propto \sqrt {F}$
    The frequency is proportional to the square root of the tension (stretching force). The squared tension yields in a doubled frequency which is one octave higher.
  • $f_0 \propto \frac {1} {\sqrt {\mu}}$
    The frequency is inversely proportional to the square root of the mass per unit length. So to get the frequency one octave higher the mass per unit length must be reduced by the inversed square (1/4).

where $f$ is frequency [Hz], $L$ is length [m], $F$ is the tension [N] and $\mu$ is the mass per unit length [kg/m].

The mass per unit length obviously depends on the string material and diameter. The mass per unit length (sometimes called unit weight) might be provided by the string manufacturer, but can be calculated based on diameter and material. In the latter case we need string diameter $d$ and the material density $\rho$. The formula to calculate mass per unit length:
$$\mu = \pi . \frac {1}{2}{d}^2 . \rho$$

The three equations above combine to Mersenne's Law formula: $$f_0 = \frac{v}{\lambda} = \frac{1}{2L}\sqrt\frac{F}{\mu}$$ where $\mu$ is given or calculated, wave speed $v = \sqrt\frac{F}{\mu}$ and wave length $\lambda = {2L}$.

Derived formulas¶

  • String tension: $F = \mu . \lambda^2 . {f}^2$
  • String diameter: $d = \frac{\sqrt {F}}{\sqrt {\pi\rho}.{L}.{f}}$

Constants¶

Having a tuning reference A of 440 Hz, the frequency for each guitar string is:

string E (low) A D G B E (high)
number 6 5 4 3 2 1
frequency (Hz) 82.41 110.00 146.83 196.00 246.94 329.63

Density of string material most often seen on classical guitars. Required when calculating mass per unit length:

material density [kg/m$^3$]
carbon 1790
gut 1360
nylon 1140

The exact density may vary per manufacturer and can depend on the material species.

  • Wave length is based on the speed of sound: 340.29 m/s
  • Standard gravity 9.80665 m/s$^2$
  • scale length (in this notebook) 25,5 in = 0.6477 m

Conversions¶

It might be necessary to convert between the US customary units system (imperial) and the Systme international (metric). This table lists the most frequently used units in string calculation:

unit U.S. customary units metric SI
length 1 in 0.0254 m
mass 1 lb 0.45359237 kg
mass/unit length 1 lb/in 17.8579673 kg/m
density 1 lb/ft$^3$ 16.01846337396 kg/m$^3$
tension 1 lb (actually lbf) 4.4482216153 N

Read in data¶

Read data of the following D'Addario string sets I use on my guitars:

  • EJ45 Normal Tension (twice due to recalculated string tensions by D'Addario)
  • EJ46 Hard Tension
  • EJ44 Extra Hard Tension

The D'Addario Tension Guide is used to get the mass per unit length (unit-weight). All units of measurement are based on the US customary units system (imperial).

In [4]:
# constants
stringFreqDict = {1 : 329.63, 2 : 246.94, 3 : 196.00, 4: 146.83, 5 : 110.00, 6: 82.41}
rho_nylon = 1140.0
scale_length = 0.6477
gravity = 9.80665
In [5]:
def convert2metric(row):
    row['diameter'] = row['diameter'] * 0.0254
    row['tension'] = row['tension'] * 4.4482216153
    row['unit-weight'] = row['unit-weight'] * 17.8579673
    return row
In [6]:
def tensionProvidedMu(string, freq = 'open'):
    return string['unit-weight'] * pow(2 * scale_length, 2) * pow(stringFreqDict[string['number']] if freq == 'open' else freq, 2)
In [7]:
def tensionCalculateMu(string, freq = 'open'):
    mu = math.pi * pow(0.5 * string['diameter'], 2) * rho_nylon
    return mu * pow(2 * scale_length, 2) * pow(stringFreqDict[string['number']] if freq == 'open' else freq, 2)
In [8]:
def calculatePitch(string):
    return 1 / (2 * scale_length) * math.sqrt((string['tension']) / string['unit-weight'])
In [9]:
def calculateDiameter(string, freq = 'open'):
    return math.sqrt(string['tension']) / (math.sqrt(math.pi * rho_nylon) * scale_length * (stringFreqDict[string['number']] if freq == 'open' else freq))

Tension calculations¶

In [10]:
# Results calculations stored in  
strings = []
tensions = []
tensionsC = []
types= []
pitches = []
diams = []
dash = '-' * 78
print(dash)
print('{:<10s}{:<8s}{:>20s}{:>20s}{:>20s}'.format('String', 'Type','Tension [N]','Pitch [Hz]','Diameter [mm]'))
print(dash)
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    string = convert2metric(row)
    strings.append(string['string'] + '(' + str(string['number']) + ')')
    types.append(string['description'])
    tension = tensionProvidedMu(string)
    tensions.append(tension)
    tensionsC.append(tensionCalculateMu(string))
    pitch = calculatePitch(string)
    pitches.append(pitch)
    diameter = calculateDiameter(string) * 1000.0 #in mm
    diams.append(diameter)
    print('{:<10s}{:<8s}{:>20.6f}{:>20.6f}{:>20.6f}'.format(string['string'] + '(' + str(string['number']) + ')', string['description'],tension,pitch,diameter))
string_data = {'String' : strings, 'Type' : types, 'Tension [N]' : tensions, 'Pitch [Hz]' : pitches, 'Diameter [mm]' : diams}
dfTension = pd.DataFrame(string_data, columns = ['String', 'Type', 'Tension [N]', 'Pitch [Hz]', 'Diameter [mm]'])

Out[12]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, "Calculated tensions from D'Addario given unit weight")
  • see printed table above for the calculated values
  • EJ45-New is exactly the same string set as EJ45, except for tension recalculation by D'Addario resulting in higher tensions for EJ45-New.
  • the above calculation is amongst others based on the unit weight in D'Addario's Tension Guide where the old EJ45 tensions are listed. That explains why the scatter plot has the same tensions for EJ45 and EJ45-New.
  • for all types the E(1) and D(4) strings expose the highest tensions while B(2) and (G(3) the lowest
  • types EJ44 and EJ46 have the same D(4) and A(5) strings
  • apart from EJ45 the calculated tensions are somewhat lower than indicated on the D'Addario string set packaging and website. I guess this is due to old unit weights in the Tension Guide

Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Calculated pitch')
  • see printed table above for the calculated values
  • as expected bass strings have lower frequencies
  • especially for string E(1) the frequencies are about 10 Hz higher than the given 329.63 Hz for this string. This is caused by a higher tension in the daddariostrings.csv file (mentioned on string set packaging and website) in comparison with the tensions in D'Addario's Tension Guide. Unit weight $\mu$ is taken from this Tension Guide.

Tension for specific notes¶

  • E(6) tuning to D gives it a 73.416 Hz pitch
  • G(3) to F# gives a 184.997 Hz pitch

for index,row in df.iterrows():
    if row.string=='G' or (row.string=='E' and row.number==6):
        string = convert2metric(row)
        print('{:<10s}{:<8s}{:>20.6f}{:>20.6f}'.format(string['string'] + '(' + str(string['number']) + ')', string['description'],stringFreqDict[string['number']],tensionProvidedMu(string)))
        pitch = 184.997 if row.string=='G' else 73.416
        print('{:<10s}{:<8s}{:>20.6f}{:>20.6f}'.format(string['string'] + '(' + str(string['number']) + ')', string['description'],pitch,tensionProvidedMu(string, pitch)))
